We assumed that Y(s; t) be the realization of the spatiotemporal process Y(, ; ,) that indicates the weekly average infected rate of Visceral leishmaniasis in human(VLH) at locations i = 1, 2, …, m located at si stations and week t = 1, 2, …, T, We assumed the following spatiotemporal model;
Y(si;t)=βZ(si,t)+Φ(si,t)+ϵ(si,t)(4)
Where; Z(si, t) = Z1(si, t), …, Zp(si, t) denote the vector of covariates and β = (β1, β2, …, βp)′ is a coefficient of the vector, Moreover; ϵ(si,t)∼N(0,σϵ2) is spatiotemporal Gaussian white noise process both serially and spatially uncorrelated. ϵ(si, t) is the realization of state process of the unobserved rate of infection of VLH. We assumed the spatiotemporal Gaussian field process that changes in time with first-order autoregressive dynamics with a coefficient of λ and colored innovations is given by;
Φ(si,t)=λΦ(si,t-1)+γ(si,t)(5)
For t = 2, 3, …, T where |λ| < 1 and Φ(si, 1) is derived from a stationary Gaussian distribution ∼N(0,σγ21-λ2) Moreover, γ(si, t) has a zero-mean Gaussian distribution, is assumed to be temporally independent and characterized by spatiotemporal covariance functions;
Cov(γ(si,t),γ(si′,t′))={0,ift≠t′σγ2(r)ift=t′
for i ≠ j the purely spatial correlation function C(r) is depending on the location si and sj only through the euclidian spatial distance r = ||si − sj|| ∈ R. Thus, the process is second order stationary and isotropic [10]. It follows that Var(γ(si,t))=σγ2 for each si and t. The Spatial correlation function is defined as a Matern function;
C(r)=1Γ(v)2v-1(kr)vκv(kr)
With κv denoting the modified Bessel function of the second kind and order v > 0, The parameter v, which usually kept stable measures of the degree of smoothness of the process and its integer value decides the mean square differentiability of the process, k > 0 is the scaling parameter related to the range ρ we use empirically derived definition ρ=8vk with ρ corresponding the distance where the spatial correlation is close to 0.1 [8], [20]. From Eqs (4) and (5) by collecting observation in vector t we have:
Yt=(y(s1,t),y(s2,t),…,y(sm,t))′Zt=(z(s1,t),z(s2,t),…,z(sm,t))′Φt=(Φ(s1,t),Φ(s2,t),…,Φ(sm,t))′ϵt=(ϵ(s1,t),ϵ(s2,t),…,ϵ(sm,t))′
It follows that;
Yt=βZt+Φt+ϵt(6)
ϵt∼N(0,σϵ2Im) and also;
Φt=λΦt-1+γt(7)
γt∼N(0,Σ=σϵ2Σ˜), we assume is coming from the stationary distribution of AR(1) process with, Φ1∼N(0,Σ1-λ2)=∼N(0,σϵ2Σ˜1-λ2) Moreover, the dense correlation matrix of dimension m with an element C(||si − sj||), Where C(r) is a Matern covariance function;
C(r)=1Γ(v)2v-1(kr)vκv(kr)
and parameterized by κ and v. Let Θ=(β,σϵ2,λ,σγ2,κ) denote the parameter of the vector to be estimated, thus, the joint posterior distribution is given by;
P(Θ,Φ|Y)∝P(Y|Θ,Φ)P(Φ|Θ)P(Θ)(8)
Where P(.) denotes the probability density functions, Y = (Yt) and Φ = (Φt) with t = 2, 3, …, T and assume the hyper parameters are independent P(Θ)=∏i=1dim(Θ)P(Θi), The left-hand side of Eq (8) above is the joint posterior distribution and the right-hand side of Eq (8), P(Y|Θ, Φ) is the data model (likelihood of the data), P(Φ|Θ) is the latent (unobserved) process model and P(Θ) is the parameter model. From Eq (6) above we have
Yt=βZt+Φt+ϵt
ϵt∼N(0,σϵ2Im) Thus; the data model (likelihood of the data) can be written as
P(Yt|Φ,Θ)∼N(βZt+Φt,σϵ2Im)=(12πσϵ)mTexp-12∑i=1T(ϵtϵt′σϵ2)
but ϵt = Yt − βZt − Φt
P(Yt|Φ,Θ)∝(σϵ2)-mT2exp-12σϵ2[∑i=1T((Yt-βZt-Φt)(Yt-βZt-Φt)′)](9)
The joint distribution of spatiotemporal process model is can be factorized as with the total law of probability and Markovian process;
P(Φ1,Φ2,…,ΦT|Θ)=P(ΦT|ΦT-1,ΦT-2,…,Φ1,Θ)×…,P(Φ2|Φ1,Θ)×P(Φ1|Θ)
using a Markovian process assumption we have;
P(ΦT|ΦT-1,ΦT-2,…,Φ1,Θ)=P(ΦT|ΦT-1,Θ)
We have the joint distribution of the process model;
P(Φ1,Φ2,…,ΦT|Θ)=P(Φ1|Θ)∏t=2TP(Φt|Φt-1,Θ)(10)
We assume the hyperparameter are independent, the parameter model is given by;
P(Θ)=∏i=1dim(Θ)P(Θi)(11)
The posterior distribution is given by the product of the data model, process model, and parameter model [21]. we assume Φ1 is AR(1) stationary process, Φ1|Θ∼N(0,Σ1-λ2), Φ1|Θ also called the initial distribution [21].
P(Φ1|Θ)=(12π|Σ1-λ2|12)mexp-12(Φ1′(Σ1-λ2)-1Φ1)
From above we define and assume Σ=σγ2Σ˜
P(Φ1|Θ)∝(σγ21-λ2)-m2|Σ˜|-12exp(-1-λ22σγ2Φ1′Σ˜-1Φ1)(12)
Also the evolution distribution; P(Φt|Φt−1, Θ) since follows an AR(1) process, Φt = λΦt−1 + γt and γt∼N(0,Σ=σϵ2Σ˜), The joint eveloution distribution is given as;
P(Φt|Φt-1,Θ)=(12πσγ2)m(T-1)|Σ˜|-(T-12)exp(-12σγ2∑i=1T(Φt-λΦt-1)Σ˜-1(Φt-λΦt-1)′)
P(Φt|Φt−1,Θ)∝(σγ2)−m(T−1)2|Σ˜|−(T−12)exp(−12σγ2∑i=1T(Φt−λΦt−1)Σ˜−1(Φt−λΦt−1)′)(13)
the joint process model is expressed as the product of the joint initial distribution and the joint evolution distribution [21], Thus from Eqs (12) and (13), we have the process model the joint distribution given by;
P(Φ1,Φ2,…,ΦT|Θ)=P(Φ1|Θ)∏t=2TP(Φt|Φt-1,Θ)
∝(σγ21-λ2)-m2|Σ˜|-12exp(-1-λ22σγ2Φ1′Σ˜-1Φ1)×(σγ2)-m(T-1)2|Σ˜|-(T-12)×exp(-12σγ2∑i=1T(Φt-λΦt-1)Σ˜-1(Φt-λΦt-1)′)(14)
The parameter model also from Eq (11) above;
P(Θ)=∏i=1dim(Θ)P(Θi)
Thus, the joint posterior model is the product of the data model, process model and parameter model [21] give us;
A=(σϵ2)-mT2exp-12σϵ2[∑i=1T((Yt-βZt-Φt)(Yt-βZt-Φt)′)](15)
B=(σγ21-λ2)-m2|Σ˜|-12exp(-1-λ22σγ2Φ1′Σ˜-1Φ1)×(σγ2)-m(T-1)2|Σ˜|-(T-12)×exp(-12σγ2∑i=1T(Φt-λΦt-1)Σ˜-1(Φt-λΦt-1)′)(16)
C=∏i=1dim(Θ)P(Θi)(17)
The joint posterior distribution;
P(Θ,Φ|Y)∝P(Y|Θ,Φ)P(Φ|Θ)P(Θ)
From Eqs (15) to (17) the joint posterior distribution is approximated by;
P(Θ,Φ|Y)∝A×B×C(18)
where |Σ˜| is the determinant of the dense m-dimensional correlation matrix Σ˜.

For each time point t = 1, 2, 3…, T, the Matern field γt in Eq (7) is characterized through GMRF, γ˜t∼N(0,Qs-1) where, Qs is the precision matrix originates from the SPDE approach. The matrix Qs does not change in time because of the serial independence assumption of Eq (5) and its dimension n is given by the number of vertices of the domain triangulation. In this manner Eq (7) can modify as;
Φt=λΦt-1+γt˜(23)
γt˜∼N(0,Qs-1)
for t = 1, 2, 3…, T with Φ1∼N(0,Qs-11-λ2) follows that the joint distribution of Tn dimensional GMRF, Φ=(Φ1′,Φ2′,…,ΦT′) is given by;
Φ∼N(0,Q-1)(24)
Where, Q = Qs ⊗ QT and QT is T- dimensional precession matrix of the autoregressive process of order 1 in Eq (23). Equation Eq (6) we can rewrite as also;
Yt=βZt+HΦt+ϵt,ϵt∼N(0,σϵ2Im)(25)
where the (m × n) dimensional matrix H selects the value of the GMRF Φt for each observation vector Yt. In particular, H is a sparse matrix with only one unit element for each row and such that;
Y(si,t)=βZ(si,t)+∑i=1nHijΦt+ϵ(si,t)
Where Hij = 1 if the triangulation vector j is placed at location si and 0 otherwise.

Let X = (Φ, β) mean the basic latent field with a priori independent parts. We dole out a vague Gaussian with known precession to β and the Gaussian Markov Random Field (GMRF) distribution to Φ in Eq (24). Consequently the density P(X|Θ) is a Gaussian distribution with mean zero and precession matrix Q with hyperparameter vector (σγ2,λ,κ). Also, we have the observation Y = (Yt) is normally distributed and conditionally independent given X and σϵ2. Thus, Θ=(σγ2,σϵ2,λ,κ) is the hyper parameter vector, The joint posterior distribution is given by;
P(X,Θ|Y)=P(Θ)P(X|Θ)∏t=1TP(Yt|Θ,X)(26)
Where P(Yt|Θ,X)∼N(βZt+HΦt,σϵ2Im) is the conditional distribution of the infected rate of VLH observation at time t defined by Eq (25). Thus, the posterior marginal distribution of the latent field and the hyper paramater is given by;
P(Xi|Y)=∫P(Xi|Θ,Y)P(Θ|Y)dΘ(27)
P(Θj|Y)=∫P(Θ|Y)dΘ-j(28)
for i = 1, 2, 3, …, T + p and j = 1, 2, …, 4.
